Commands learned:
1. du -- shows file storage usage. -h makes it human readable. sort -h makes it human readable
2. df -- estimates file system free space
3. history -- shows history of commands, can be combined with less, find, or grep to find and run specific commands in
the past
--> finding command history and typing !-number- runs the command
4. ps -- shows current processes being run, as well as the process id time ran
5. top -- provides extensive information on currently running programs and processes, with loads of data like memory or 
disk usage
6. kill -- kills programs. -9 is hard kill -TERM is gentle kill. kill using process ids
7. killall -- kills programs by name. can be done to kill multiple programs at the same time.
8. jobs -- shows currrently running commands. 
9. ctrl z -> suspends programs
10. fg -> continues programs in the visible terminal
11. bg -> continues programs in the background
12. sleep -> provides a pause to programs
13. & -> put at the end of commands to run them in the background in default

